{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Summary\nA Jira issue created directly in Jira (no rebar binding) is never adopted into the local store at steady state. Proven: REB-532 (\"EXPERIMENT (delete me): assignee clobber repro\", Bug, To Do) is fetched every pass but has no binding and no local ticket.\n\n## Root Cause (edge-triggered adoption + prev_snapshot as a false \"handled\" proxy)\n- REB-532 IS fetched — the inbound JQL has no rebar-label filter (`fetcher.py:67-79`).\n- The binding-aware `inbound_differ.compute_inbound_mutations` skips any unbound issue by design (`inbound_differ.py:719-722`, docstring `:4-6` \"local is source of truth\"); it only emits `update`, never `create`.\n- Inbound-CREATE lives only in `differ.compute_mutations`, which production calls as `compute_mutations(prev_snapshot, curr_snapshot)` — BOTH Jira snapshots (`reconcile.py:901-903`). Create fires only for a key in `curr` but NOT `prev` (`differ.py:457-469`) = \"new since last pass\".\n- `prev_snapshot` means \"seen in a prior fetch\", used as a proxy for \"already handled\" — but it is NOT \"bound to a local ticket\". `reconcile.py:1407` advances prev via `shutil.copy2(curr, prev)` UNCONDITIONALLY, regardless of whether adoption actually landed. So once REB-532 is in prev it is in both snapshots -> present-in-both (field-drift) branch -> never re-adopted. There is NO level-triggered reconvergence that asks \"fetched key has no binding -> adopt\".\n- Runtime proof: `compute_mutations(prev={}, curr={REB-532}) -> 1 inbound create`; `compute_mutations(prev={REB-532}, curr={REB-532}) -> 0`.\n\n## Why the test suite misses it\n- The differ unit tests model `compute_mutations(arg1, arg2)` as `(local_state, jira_state)` (`test_differ.py:1-13`), so an unbound issue is always absent from arg1 and create always fires — validating a contract production does NOT use.\n- Every adoption test uses `local={}` (empty prev) incl. the closest-named `test_unbound_jira_issue_without_rebar_id_label_still_creates` (`test_differ.py:542`).\n- The only two-pass integration test binds everything in pass 1 (`test_reconcile_idempotency.py:268,291`), so the \"in prev but still unbound\" state is never constructed; the unconditional `copy2` at `reconcile.py:1407` is untested.\n- `inbound_differ` tests assert unbound issues are ignored (`test_inbound_differ.py:112`), entrenching the skip.\n\n## Reproduction Steps\n1. Create an issue directly in Jira REB (no rebar-id), e.g. REB-532.\n2. Let >= 2 reconcile passes run (so it enters prev_snapshot).\n3. Run `rebar reconcile --mode dry-run` and search the plan for the issue.\n\n## Expected vs Actual\n- Expected: a Jira-native issue is adopted into the local store (a `jira-*` local ticket + confirmed binding) and stays converged.\n- Actual: it is fetched but never adopted; permanently orphaned in Jira.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A Jira-native issue with no binding is adopted into local within one pass, regardless of whether it is already in `prev_snapshot` (level-triggered, not just edge-triggered) — without re-deriving all historical creates every pass (respect the prev_snapshot perf optimisation).\n- [ ] `prev_snapshot` advance (`reconcile.py:1407`) no longer marks an issue \"handled\" when adoption did not actually bind it (decouple prev-advance from adoption success), OR a binding-aware reconvergence adopts unbound fetched issues.\n- [ ] A RED test constructs the failing state: the SAME key present in both `prev_snapshot` and `curr_snapshot` with NO binding, then asserts it is adopted.\n- [ ] REB-532 is adopted (or explicitly excluded as a test artifact) after the fix.\n\n## Notes\nDiscovered comparing Jira REB vs local. Files: `differ.py`, `inbound_differ.py`, `reconcile.py`, `fetcher.py`, `apply_inbound.py`; tests under `tests/unit/rebar_reconciler/diffing/`, `tests/integration/rebar_reconciler/`.\n\n## Guardrails (must-preserve — prior-art + archaeology; folds in the corrected plan)\nApproved policy: ADOPT unbound Jira-native issues (test-ticket hygiene is the creator's responsibility). But adoption is gated:\n- [ ] Adoption MUST consult `bindings-retired.json` (`is_retired`) so a locally-archived-then-retired issue is not resurrected into a delete/re-adopt loop (interacts with C's GC).\n- [ ] Run the rebar-id label audit (L9) and the label-derived-binding suppression (L10, bug 4354) FIRST: an issue already carrying a `rebar-id:`/`rebar-id-` label is bound — adopting it double-writes identity and recreates the phantom `jira-dig-NNNN` + ghost-label defect and can trip the double-bind quarantine (L11).\n- [ ] Seed the per-binding BASELINE from the adopted issue's fields on bind, so the first outbound diff is EMPTY (echo suppression, L2).\n- [ ] Adoption `create + bind` is keyed on the external id (idempotency/dedup key) so two overlapping passes cannot create duplicate local items before the binding lands [prior art: K8s read-all-then-write].\n- [ ] Level-triggered: `unbound = fetched_keys - bound_keys` each pass (replaces the `prev_snapshot` edge-trigger), so a failed adoption re-fires until it binds. Do NOT rely on `prev_snapshot` for the trigger.\n- [ ] Proven by the convergence property with an issue present in BOTH prev/curr snapshots and unbound (the exact steady-state cell the current suite never constructs)."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783078756402860001,"uuid":"c708e4ea-1604-4331-9f78-9c54faff48ed"}